    <!-- Final interpretation sentences per card -->
    <string name="confidence_interp_high">Excellent inter-model agreement: the spread is within the numerical noise expected at this lead time.</string>
    <string name="confidence_interp_medium">Moderate agreement. The spread reflects parameterization differences between models; the actual value will most likely sit near the mean.</string>
    <string name="confidence_interp_low">Significant disagreement. At this lead time, the high-resolution models no longer provide data and those that remain carry different biases.</string>
    <string name="confidence_interp_precip_dry">No model picks up a precipitating system. This is one of the most reliable verdicts the ensemble can deliver.</string>
    <string name="confidence_interp_precip_rain">All see rain, but intensity depends on the model. Fine-resolution models capture convective cores better.</string>
    <string name="confidence_interp_precip_divided">Typical disagreement for transitional situations (fronts, scattered showers). Watch the next run.</string>

    <!-- Educational section -->
    <string name="confidence_section_why">Why models differ</string>
    <string name="confidence_why_resolution_body">A model\'s resolution is the size of each computational grid cell. The finer it is, the better the model captures local phenomena like convective showers, terrain effects or sea breezes. But this comes at a cost: very high-resolution models are expensive to run and their forecast horizon is short.</string>
    <string name="confidence_why_resolution_tip">Useful rule of thumb: at 24-48 h over France, AROME HD (1.5 km) catches details that GFS (13 km) or ECMWF (25 km) miss. Beyond 2-3 days, global models take the lead because they capture the large-scale circulation better.</string>

